Answer 1.1, Baseline (4p)¶

  • Dense network, at least 3 layers, shaped like a pyramid
    • Last layer: 10 nodes, sigmoid.
    • Loss: categorical cross-entropy. Metric: accuracy
  • No preprocessing, regularization. Get at least 70% accuracy.
  • Explain design decisions. Discuss performance.
    • Does it overfit (large/growing gap between loss and val_loss)?
I started by trying a 32->16->10 network, which offered very poor performance. I then decided to add a layer to form a 64->32->16->10 network and already that yielded a much better result. The final choice comes from noticing that the model performed worse with a big first layer and then just by trying to vary the parameters. The model achieves around 72% on both training and validation.  (length: 392)

def build_model_1_1():
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Reshape((3072,), input_shape=(32,32,3)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(49, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(31, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(23, activation='relu'))
    model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

I first started with simple RGB to gray conversion which gave me about the same results as model 1_1. Answer 1.3, Tune (4p)¶

  • Regularize the model. What works best?
    • Should consider batch normalization, dropout, l1/l2 regularization (or Nesterov)
  • Tune other hyperparameters (e.g. learning rate, batch size,...) as you see fit.
    • At least consider tuning learning rate, ideally also momentum, decay, other optimizers
  • Explain your findings and final design decisions. Discuss the results.
    • Should be better, at least it shouldn't overfit
I tried multiple combinations of l1, l2 and l1_l2 regularizers. The best results were obtained by applying a L2 regularizer on the model and a L1 regularizer on the biases. A tiny learning rate on the L2 regularizer showed quite some improvement. The model now is slightly more accurate but still overfits the data a bit.  (length: 323)

Max val score: 74.97%

def build_model_1_3():
    model = models.Sequential()
    model.add(layers.Reshape((1024,), input_shape=(32,32,1,)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(49, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001), bias_regularizer=regularizers.l1(0.001)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(31, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001), bias_regularizer=regularizers.l1(0.001)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(23, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.0001), bias_regularizer=regularizers.l1(0.001)))
    model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    
    opti = optimizers.RMSprop(lr=0.0005)
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'],
                  optimizer=opti)
    return model

Answer 2.1, ConvNet (7p)¶

  • Build a sequential ConvNet, get at least 90% accuracy.
    • Conv2D layers, input shape (32,32,1)
    • Consider using blocks of Conv2D layers with maxpooling in between
    • Use zero-padding in Conv2D layers because the images are small
    • At least one dense hidden layer and dense output layer (sigmoid)
    • Consider adding batch normalization, dropout
    • Consider small dropout rates in beginning, larger dropout rates later in network
    • Consider other optimizers and tuning learning rate, momentum,...
  • Explain what you did and why (800 chars). Is it working well?
    • Should be quite elaborate and sensible
I started with two blocks of 32 and 64 nodes and this already gave a decent 85% accuracy. So I decided to duplicate these blocks and it jumped to about 89%. By applying a leaky ReLU activation and normalizing the data, the model started reaching 90%+ accuracy. I then decided to try and add a maxpooling2D layer to each block which made the accuracy of the training data jump to 95%. Finally, by adding an extra ReLU activationa and a dropout layer with value 0.2, the model achieved 96% accuracy on the training dataset and saw for the first time an accuracy of 90%+ on the validation dataset. Before this, it only reached about 88% on the validation.  (length: 654)

def build_model_2_1():
    
    model = models.Sequential()
    # Layers
    model.add(layers.Input(shape=(32, 32, 1,)))
    
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3)))
    model.add(layers.LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding='same'))
    
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding='same'))
    
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding='same'))
    
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding='same'))
    
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding='same'))
    
    model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(layers.LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), padding='same'))
    
    model.add(layers.Flatten())
    model.add(layers.Dense(32))
    model.add(layers.LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    
    model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'mse', metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    return model

Between 5 and 7, a vertical flip of a 5 is often misinterpreted for a 7. Most other misclassifications are du to a very blurry image or when an image has multiple digits.  (length: 322)

Answer 4.1, Fast feature extraction (5p)¶

  • Import the VGG16 model, pretrained on ImageNet
  • Freeze convolutional base, adds a dense layer
  • Consider unfreezing the last few convolutional layers and evaluate whether that works better
    • Check if they do. It is very likely to help.
  • Discuss the observed performance
    • Should get around 80% accuracy
Running VGG16 with all layers frozen returned an accuracy of about 55% on the training dataset after 15 epochs. Unfreezing the last block (block5) yields much better results, with an accuracy of around 94% on the training dataset and 82% on the validation. However, the model starts overfitting after 10 epochs or so, which is why we observe a 12% drop between training and validation.  (length: 387)

def build_model_4_1():
    model = models.Sequential()
    vgg_model = VGG16(include_top=False, weights='imagenet', input_shape=(32,32,3,))
    
    # Freeze layers
    for layer in vgg_model.layers:
        if "block5" not in layer.name:
            layer.trainable = False
    
    # Add VGG16
    model.add(vgg_model)
    # Add dense layer
    model.add(layers.Flatten())
    model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'],
                  optimizer='rmsprop')
    return model
